<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-317-922  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 317 922.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  May 29 1989 v8 n11 p44(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM offers one-step EDI shopping with new series. (electronic datainterchange)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taft, Darryl K.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     United States. Office of Management and BudgetElectronic Data InterchangeMarketing StrategyData CommunicationsConnectivityProduct DevelopmentStandardization.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM Offers One-Stop EDI Shopping With New SeriesandM;IBM Corp. has announced a series of electronic data interchange (EDI)translation software, enabling the company to offer one-stop EDI shopping forits customers.andM;The new products, featured in the IBM Expedite DataInterchange Series, enabledifferent organizations electronically to exchange standard format businessdocuments, such as purchase orders, invoices and order acknowledgements.andM;By introducing its new EDI software, IBM now offers a comprehensive series ofEDI products that can decrease significantly the time spent manuallyprocessing and mailing business documents and help minimize costlybookkeeping errors, IBM officials said.andM;Meanwhile, EDI use continues to grow in the government, with the DefenseDepartment as well as the Office of Management and Budget encouraging its usefor standard agency business transactions.andM;Agencies such as the Customs Service, the General Services Administration,the Navy, the Defense Logistics Agency, and the Commerce and Veterans Affairsdepartments have used EDI successfully to save time and money in everydaybusiness dealings.andM;IBM's translation products will run on the IBM Personal System/2, ApplicationSystem/400, System/36, System/38, as well as IBM mainframe computers runningthe MVS/ESA and MVS/XA operating systems.andM;&quot;This announcement shows IBM's growing commitment to the EDI marketplace,&quot;said Ned Lautenbach, IBM vice president and general manager of the company'sApplication Solutions line of business.andM;&quot;State-of-the-art translator software from our Application Systems Division,combined with networking services from the IBM Information Network andsupport from our Systems Integration Division, establish IBM as an industryleader in offering its customers one-stop EDI shopping -- a total, end-to-endEDI solution,&quot; Lautenbach said.andM;The new products translate documents created on an organization's computerinto standard EDI data formats so the documents can be transmittedelectronically across a network to vendor, supplier and customer locations.andM;At the receiving end, another translator program performs the reverseoperation, translating the EDI-formatted document into the appropriateapplication format.andP;  As a result, differences in computer types and dataformats are minimized.andM;The new IBM products support American National Standards Institute X12standards for use in the United States, and the United Nations/Edifactstandards for international use, IBM officials said.andM;Company officials also said IBM will support Uniform Communications Standardsand Transportation Data Coordinating Committee standards in the AS/400,System/36 and System/38 translators, and that it intends to support thesestandards with OS/2 and MVS translators.andM;Licensing prices for the new DataInterchange Series products range from $4,000 on the PS/2 to $ 38,000 for the most advanced mainframe configuration.andO;While the mainframe version is available now, the AS/400, System/36 andSystem/38 versions will be available in the third quarter of this year.andP;  ThePS/2 version will be available in the first quarter of 1990.andO;</TEXT></DOC>